Robinson (who also, memorably, recorded the construction of the London Eye) describes his time-lapse technique as “like a meditation”, allowing the human eye to see change in ways we could never otherwise perceive. The images his numerous cameras snapped once every 30 minutes for six years enabled weeks and months of frantic and complex construction work to be distilled into seconds.
